I"ç<p>There are six (6) basic trigonometric functions in trigonometry, namely: sine, cosine, tangent, cosecant, secant, and cotangent. These are abbreviated as: sin, cos, tan, csc, sec, and cot, respectively. Consider \fref{fig:parts of a right triangle relative to the angle theta}, the angle $\theta$ on the right triangle shown can be evaluated using these trigonometric functions. Moreover, these functions can be expressed as ratios of the sides of the right triangle.</p>

<figure style="text-align: center;">
  <img src="/images/content/DC/DC-9.2.1.png" alt="my alt text" width="200px" />
  <figcaption><em><p>Figure 1: Angle denoted by the greek symbol theta, $\theta$</p>
</em></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>\typB{Six Basic Trigonometric Functions}
%
\begin{minipage}[c]{0.55\linewidth}
%	
	\begin{align<em>}
		\sin \theta &amp;= \ufrac{opposite}{hypotenuse} = \frac{y}{r}<br />
		&amp;   \csc \theta &amp;= \ufrac{hypotenuse}{opposite} = \frac{r}{y}  <br />
		\cos \theta &amp;= \ufrac{adjacent}{hypotenuse} = \frac{x}{r}<br />
		&amp;   \sec \theta &amp;= \ufrac{hypotenuse}{adjacent} = \frac{r}{x}  <br />
		\tan \theta &amp;= \ufrac{opposite}{\phantom{O}adjacent\phantom{o}} = \frac{y}{x}<br />
		&amp;   \cot \theta &amp;= \ufrac{\phantom{O}adjacent\phantom{o}}{opposite} = \frac{x}{y}  \		
	\end{align</em>}
%
\end{minipage}
\begin{minipage}[c]{0.4\linewidth}
\centering
%
